@NODE "GetDragInfo" "GetDragInfo()"
@{b}

    NAME@{ub}
	GetDragInfo - create a @{"DragInfo" LINK "dopus/drag.h/File" 14} structure@{b}

    SYNOPSIS@{ub}
	GetDragInfo(window, rastport, width, height, need_gels)
		      A0       A1       D0     D1       D2

	@{"DragInfo" LINK "dopus/drag.h/File" 14} *GetDragInfo(struct Window *, struct RastPort *,
			      long, long, long);@{b}

    FUNCTION@{ub}
	Creates a @{"DragInfo" LINK "dopus/drag.h/File" 14} structure that is used to implement drag and drop.
	Drags are inherently attached to a particular RastPort (usually either
	a screen's or a window's). The drag system is implemented using BOBs,
	which require a GelsInfo structure to be attached to the destination
	RastPort. This routine can do this for you if you desire.@{b}

    INPUTS@{ub}
	window - Window to attach BOB to (or NULL if rastport is supplied)
	rastport - RastPort to attach BOB to (if not a window)
	width - width of drag image
	height - height of drag image
	need_gels - set to TRUE if you would like this routine to allocate
		    and initialise a GelsInfo automatically@{b}

    RESULT@{ub}
	If successful, a @{"DragInfo" LINK "dopus/drag.h/File" 14} structure is returned. Nothing is displayed
	on-screen; you must create the image and display it using the other
	library calls. Once you have the @{"DragInfo" LINK "dopus/drag.h/File" 14} structure, you can
	initialise the 'flags' field as described in the introduction.@{b}

