@NODE "IFFOpen" "IFFOpen()"
@{b}

    NAME@{ub}
	IFFOpen - open an IFF file@{b}

    SYNOPSIS@{ub}
	IFFOpen(name, mode, form)
		 A0    D0    D1

	APTR IFFOpen(char *, USHORT, ULONG);@{b}

    FUNCTION@{ub}
	This routine opens either a disk-based file or the clipboard for
	IFF reading/writing. This and the other IFF routines in the
	dopus5.library are far simpler (and seem to be less buggy) than the
	iffparse.library functions. These routines were specifically designed
	to make the reading and writing of "normal" IFF files as easy as
	possible. They use the buffered IO routines for high performance.
	They do not support LISTs, CATs or other complicated IFF structures.@{b}

    INPUTS@{ub}
	name - Filename or clipboard unit to open.
	mode - Mode to open in :

		   @{"IFF_READ" LINK "dopus/iff.h/File" 11}       - open for reading
		   @{"IFF_WRITE" LINK "dopus/iff.h/File" 12}      - open for writing
		   @{"IFF_CLIP_READ" LINK "dopus/iff.h/File" 14}  - open clipboard for reading
		   @{"IFF_CLIP_WRITE" LINK "dopus/iff.h/File" 15} - open clipboard for writing

	       This flag can be set in conjunction with @{"IFF_WRITE" LINK "dopus/iff.h/File" 12} :

		   @{"IFF_SAFE" LINK "dopus/iff.h/File" 16}       - backup existing file

	form - If this is not 0, it specifies an IFF FORM. If you open
	       the file for reading, it will be tested against this FORM and
	       the open will fail if the FORM does not match. If you open
	       for writing, this specifies the FORM of the file to be
	       created.@{b}

    RESULT@{ub}
	If successful, returns an IFF handle which you use in all subsequent
	calls to the IFF routines. Returns 0 on failure, and IoErr() is set
	to the reason for the failure.@{b}

    NOTES@{ub}
	To use the clipboard, you must specify either @{"IFF_CLIP_READ" LINK "dopus/iff.h/File" 14} or
	@{"IFF_CLIP_WRITE" LINK "dopus/iff.h/File" 15}. The clipboard unit you want is passed as the name
	parameter. For example, to open clipboard unit 3 to write an ILBM,

	    handle = IFFOpen( (char *)3, @{"IFF_CLIP_WRITE" LINK "dopus/iff.h/File" 15}, ID_ILBM );

	If you specify @{"IFF_WRITE" LINK "dopus/iff.h/File" 12}|@{"IFF_SAFE" LINK "dopus/iff.h/File" 16}, and the file you are creating
	already exists, it will be renamed to a temporary filename. When
	@{"IFFClose()" LINK "IFFClose"} is called, the temporary file will be deleted. If you
	call @{"IFFFailure()" LINK "IFFFailure"} because of a failure at some stage, it sets a flag
	which causes the old file to be restored.@{b}

    SEE ALSO@{ub}
	@{"IFFClose()" LINK "IFFClose"}, @{"IFFFailure()" LINK "IFFFailure"}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "IFFPopChunk" "IFFPopChunk()"
@{b}

    NAME@{ub}
	IFFPopChunk - flush the chunk cache@{b}

    SYNOPSIS@{ub}
	IFFPopChunk(handle)
		      A0

	long IFFPopChunk(APTR);@{b}

    FUNCTION@{ub}
	This function flushes the current chunk write cache and writes the
	chunk to disk.@{b}

    INPUTS@{ub}
	handle - IFF handle@{b}

    RESULT@{ub}
	The current chunk is written to disk. Returns TRUE if successful.@{b}

    SEE ALSO@{ub}
	@{"IFFOpen()" LINK "IFFOpen"}, @{"IFFPushChunk()" LINK "IFFPushChunk"}, @{"IFFWriteChunkBytes()" LINK "IFFWriteChunkBytes"}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "IFFPushChunk" "IFFPushChunk()"
@{b}

    NAME@{ub}
	IFFPushChunk - start writing a chunk@{b}

    SYNOPSIS@{ub}
	IFFPushChunk(handle, id)
		       A0    D0

	long IFFPushChunk(APTR, ULONG);@{b}

    FUNCTION@{ub}
	This routine initialises a new chunk to be written to the file.
	It is similar in concept to the PushChunk() routine in
	iffparse.library, but does not support nesting of chunks. Therefore,
	you should always call @{"IFFPopChunk()" LINK "IFFPopChunk"} before you call IFFPushChunk()
	again.@{b}

    INPUTS@{ub}
	handle - IFF handle
	id - ID of chunk to write@{b}

    RESULT@{ub}
	The chunk is initialised for writing. The usual procedure is :

	    1. IFFPushChunk()
	    2. One or more calls to @{"IFFWriteChunkBytes()" LINK "IFFWriteChunkBytes"}
	    3. @{"IFFPopChunk()" LINK "IFFPopChunk"}@{b}

    SEE ALSO@{ub}
	@{"IFFOpen()" LINK "IFFOpen"}, @{"IFFWriteChunkBytes()" LINK "IFFWriteChunkBytes"}, @{"IFFPopChunk()" LINK "IFFPopChunk"}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "IFFReadChunkBytes" "IFFReadChunkBytes()"
@{b}

    NAME@{ub}
	IFFReadChunkBytes - read data from a chunk@{b}

    SYNOPSIS@{ub}
	IFFReadChunkBytes(handle, buffer, size)
			    A0      A1     D0

	long IFFReadChunkBytes(APTR, APTR, long);@{b}

    FUNCTION@{ub}
	This routine reads data from the current position in the current
	chunk.@{b}

    INPUTS@{ub}
	handle - IFF handle
	buffer - buffer to store data
	size - amount of data to read@{b}

    RESULT@{ub}
	Returns the amount of data read or -1 for failure. Will not read
	past the end of a chunk.@{b}

