@NODE "OpenImage" "OpenImage()"
@{b}

    NAME@{ub}
	OpenImage - read an image off disk@{b}

    SYNOPSIS@{ub}
	OpenImage(name, info)
		   A0    A1

	APTR OpenImage(char *, @{"OpenImageInfo" LINK "dopus/images.h/File" 37} *);@{b}

    FUNCTION@{ub}
	The primary purpose of this function is to read an image from a file
	on disk. This routine supports ILBM brushes and pictures, animbrushes
	and Amiga icons.

	This routine is also used to create an image handle to bitmap data
	that you supply. This image handle can then be used with the image
	remapping functions.

	This function caches images based on their full pathname. If two
	copies of the same file are loaded, the first copy will be used to
	save memory.@{b}

    INPUTS@{ub}
	name - name of image to load, or NULL if you are supplying a bitmap
	info - if 'name' is NULL, this must point to an initialised
	       @{"OpenImageInfo" LINK "dopus/images.h/File" 37} structure:

		    oi_ImageData - must point to the image data. This data
		    does not need to be in chip memory.

		    oi_Palette - must point to a palette for the image, in
		    LoadRGB32() format.

		    oi_Width - width of the image

		    oi_Height - height of the image

		    oi_Depth - number of image bitplanes@{b}

    RESULT@{ub}
	Returns an image handle if it succeeds. This handle is used in
	subsequent calls to the image routines. This routine returns NULL if
	it fails.@{b}

    SEE ALSO@{ub}
	@{"CloseImage()" LINK "CloseImage"}, graphics.library/LoadRGB32()

@ENDNODE
@NODE "RemapImage" "RemapImage()"
@{b}

    NAME@{ub}
	RemapImage - remap an image@{b}

    SYNOPSIS@{ub}
	RemapImage(image, screen, remap)
		    A0      A1      A2

	BOOL RemapImage(APTR, struct Screen *, @{"ImageRemap" LINK "dopus/images.h/File" 23} *);@{b}

    FUNCTION@{ub}
	This function remaps an image to the colours of the specified screen.
	It will allocate pens from the screen if necessary (and possible).@{b}

    INPUTS@{ub}
	image - image to remap (from @{"OpenImage()" LINK "OpenImage"})
	remap - @{"ImageRemap" LINK "dopus/images.h/File" 23} structure. This structure must be initialised for
		the first call to RemapImage(). All fields must be set to
		NULL.

		For the first and subsequent calls to this function, the
		ir_Flags field can be set with the following values :

		    @{"IRF_REMAP_COL0" LINK "dopus/images.h/File" 31}      - remap colour 0 in the image
		    @{"IRF_PRECISION_EXACT" LINK "dopus/images.h/File" 32} - use best precision when pen matching
		    @{"IRF_PRECISION_ICON" LINK "dopus/images.h/File" 33}  - lower precision
		    @{"IRF_PRECISION_GUI" LINK "dopus/images.h/File" 34}   - lowest precision

		You can use the one @{"ImageRemap" LINK "dopus/images.h/File" 23} structure to remap multiple
		images, but only for the one screen. The ir_Flags field can be
		changed for every call to this function, but none of the
		other fields may be changed.@{b}

    RESULT@{ub}
	This image returns TRUE if it was able to remap the image. Once the
	image has been remapped, any call to @{"RenderImage()" LINK "RenderImage"} to display it will
	show the remapped version. Call @{"FreeRemapImage()" LINK "FreeRemapImage"} to free the remap
	and return to the original image.@{b}

    SEE ALSO@{ub}
	@{"OpenImage()" LINK "OpenImage"}, @{"RenderImage()" LINK "RenderImage"}, @{"FreeRemapImage()" LINK "FreeRemapImage"}, @{"FreeImageRemap()" LINK "FreeImageRemap"}

