@NODE "IPC_FindProc" "IPC_FindProc()"
@{b}

    NAME@{ub}
	IPC_FindProc - find an IPC process by name@{b}

    SYNOPSIS@{ub}
	IPC_FindProc(list, name, activate, data)
		      A0    A1      D0      D1

	@{"IPCData" LINK "dopus/ipc.h/File" 24} *IPC_FindProc(@{"struct ListLock" LINK "dopus/lists.h/File" 63} *, char *, BOOL, ULONG);@{b}

    FUNCTION@{ub}
	This routine searches the supplied list for a named IPC process.
	Optionally, it can send this process an IPC_ACTIVATE message with
	user-specified data.@{b}

    INPUTS@{ub}
	list - ListLock to search. This routine locks this list in shared
	       mode, and will block until the list is available.

	name - name to search for (case sensitive)

	activate - specify TRUE if you want an IPC_ACTIVATE message to be sent
		   automatically.

	data - if 'activate' is TRUE, this value will be passed in the data
	       field of the IPC_ACTIVATE command.@{b}

    RESULT@{ub}
	If the process is found, its @{"IPCData" LINK "dopus/ipc.h/File" 24} pointer is returned. To ensure
	that this pointer remains valid you should Forbid(), or lock the
	list yourself (in shared mode!).@{b}

    SEE ALSO@{ub}
	@{"IPC_Launch()" LINK "IPC_Launch"}, @{"IPC_Command()" LINK "IPC_Command"}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "IPC_Flush" "IPC_Flush()"
@{b}

    NAME@{ub}
	IPC_Flush - flush an IPC command port@{b}

    SYNOPSIS@{ub}
	IPC_Flush(ipc)
		   A0

	void IPC_Flush(@{"IPCData" LINK "dopus/ipc.h/File" 24} *);@{b}

    FUNCTION@{ub}
	This routine searches the command port for any messages and replies
	to them with an IPC_ABORT.@{b}

    INPUTS@{ub}
	ipc - @{"IPCData" LINK "dopus/ipc.h/File" 24} of the process@{b}

    RESULT@{ub}
	The port is emptied.@{b}

    NOTES@{ub}
	In practice you rarely need this function.@{b}

    SEE ALSO@{ub}
	@{"IPC_Free()" LINK "IPC_Free"}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "IPC_Free" "IPC_Free()"
@{b}

    NAME@{ub}
	IPC_Free - free an IPC process@{b}

    SYNOPSIS@{ub}
	IPC_Free(ipc)
		  A0

	void IPC_Free(@{"IPCData" LINK "dopus/ipc.h/File" 24} *);@{b}

    FUNCTION@{ub}
	This routine frees all the memory associated with an IPC process
	entry. It does NOT remove the process itself from the system. It is
	designed to be called by a process on itself, as the last step before
	exiting.@{b}

    INPUTS@{ub}
	ipc - @{"IPCData" LINK "dopus/ipc.h/File" 24} to free@{b}

    RESULT@{ub}
	The @{"IPCData" LINK "dopus/ipc.h/File" 24} handle is freed. If the process was a member of a list,
	it is removed from that list. Any commands still in its message port
	are replied to with IPC_ABORT.@{b}

    SEE ALSO@{ub}
	@{"IPC_Launch()" LINK "IPC_Launch"}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "IPC_Launch" "IPC_Launch()"
@{b}

    NAME@{ub}
	IPC_Launch - launch a new process@{b}

    SYNOPSIS@{ub}
	IPC_Launch(list, ipcptr, name, entry, stack, data, doslib)
		    A0     A1     A2     D0    D1     D2     A3

	long IPC_Launch(@{"struct ListLock" LINK "dopus/lists.h/File" 63} *, @{"IPCData" LINK "dopus/ipc.h/File" 24} **, char *,
			ULONG, ULONG, ULONG, struct Library *);@{b}

    FUNCTION@{ub}
	The IPC routines in the dopus5.library provide an easy and efficient
	way to implement multi-threading in your application. Using the
	IPC_Launch functions creates an @{"IPCData" LINK "dopus/ipc.h/File" 24}, which is a handle to a
	process. Using this handle you can easily send command between
	multiple processes.

	The important fields in the @{"IPCData" LINK "dopus/ipc.h/File" 24} structure are as follows :

	    proc	 - pointer to the Process structure
	    command_port - port to listen to for commands
	    userdata	 - user-specified data
	    memory	 - a memory pool you can use

	All Opus 5 modules are launched as IPC processes, and are passed
	a pointer to their @{"IPCData" LINK "dopus/ipc.h/File" 24} structures. They are also passed the
	address of the main Directory Opus @{"IPCData" LINK "dopus/ipc.h/File" 24} structure, which allows
	them to send direct commands to Opus.

	If you are writing a stand-alone application and wish to use the IPC
	routines, your main thread will need to create an @{"IPCData" LINK "dopus/ipc.h/File" 24} structure
	manually. It must be initialised as follows :

	    proc	 - pointer to your main Process
	    command_port - pointer to a message port
	    list	 - NULL
	    reply_port	 - pointer to a DIFFERENT message port

	IPC processes can automatically be added to a list. There is no
	need for you to keep track of a process once it has been launched,
	except that your main process can't exit while a child is still
	running (as the code would be freed).@{b}

    INPUTS@{ub}
	list - pointer to an initialise ListLock structure if you want this
	       process to be automatically added to a list (can be NULL).

	ipcptr - pointer to a pointer to @{"IPCData" LINK "dopus/ipc.h/File" 24}. If the process is launched
		 successfully, the new @{"IPCData" LINK "dopus/ipc.h/File" 24} handle will be stored in this
		 address (can be NULL).

	name - name for the new process.

	entry - pointer to code for the new process.

	stack - stack size for the new process. You can also set the
		@{"IPCF_GETPATH" LINK "dopus/ipc.h/File" 40} flag in the stack variable, to have the new
		process automatically inherit the system path list.

	data - data that is automatically passed to the new process

	doslib - you must supply a pointer to the DOS library@{b}

    RESULT@{ub}
	This routine returns 0 if the child process failed to launch.
	However, if the child process was actually launched, but failed
	to initialise because of lack of memory, or a failure in your
	user-defined initialisation code (see @{"IPC_ProcStartup" LINK "IPC_ProcStartup"}), the
	return value will still indicate success.

	A better way to test failure is to specify a variable for the 'ipcptr'
	parameter. If this is NULL after this call, the process failed to
	start.@{b}

    SEE ALSO@{ub}
	@{"IPC_ProcStartup()" LINK "IPC_ProcStartup"}, @{"IPC_Command()" LINK "IPC_Command"}, @{"IPC_Free" LINK "IPC_Free"}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "IPC_ListCommand" "IPC_ListCommand()"
@{b}

    NAME@{ub}
	IPC_ListCommand - send a command to a list of processes@{b}

    SYNOPSIS@{ub}
	IPC_ListCommand(list, command, flags, data, wait)
			 A0      D0      D1    D2    D3

	void IPC_ListCommand(@{"struct ListLock" LINK "dopus/lists.h/File" 63} *, ULONG, ULONG, ULONG, BOOL);@{b}

    FUNCTION@{ub}
	Sends the same command to every process on the supplied list.
	Optionally waits for a reply from every process.@{b}

    INPUTS@{ub}
	list - list of processes
	command - command ID to send
	flags - command flags
	data - command data
	wait - specify TRUE if you want to wait for replies@{b}

    RESULT@{ub}
	The command is sent to every process on the list. If 'wait' is
	TRUE, does not return until every process has replied.@{b}

    SEE ALSO@{ub}
	@{"IPC_Launch()" LINK "IPC_Launch"}, @{"IPC_Command()" LINK "IPC_Command"}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "IPC_ProcStartup" "IPC_ProcStartup()"
@{b}

    NAME@{ub}
	IPC_ProcStartup - startup code for an IPC process@{b}

    SYNOPSIS@{ub}
	IPC_ProcStartup(data, code)
			 A0    A1

	@{"IPCData" LINK "dopus/ipc.h/File" 24} *IPC_ProcStartup(ULONG *, ULONG *);@{b}

    FUNCTION@{ub}
	Your IPC process should call this routine as the very first
	instruction. It receives the startup message from the parent process,
	and lets you retrieve your own @{"IPCData" LINK "dopus/ipc.h/File" 24} handle.@{b}

    INPUTS@{ub}
	data - pointer to a variable to receive a pointer to the data that
	       was passed to @{"IPC_Launch" LINK "IPC_Launch"}.

	code - address of a user-supplied initialisation routine to call. If
	       you provide this, your routine is called from this function.
	       The prototype of this routine is as follows :

		    ULONG __asm code(register __a0 @{"IPCData" LINK "dopus/ipc.h/File" 24} *ipc,
				     register __a1 APTR data)

	       Your intitialisation routine receives a pointer to the @{"IPCData" LINK "dopus/ipc.h/File" 24}
	       handle of the new process, and a pointer to the data passed
	       to @{"IPC_Launch" LINK "IPC_Launch"}. This routine can do pretty much anything, but
	       you should keep it as simple as possible (there should
	       certainly be no IPC functions called from within it).
	       Your routine should return FALSE for failure and TRUE for
	       success. If it returns FALSE, the IPC_ProcStartup() call will
	       return NULL, and the new process should then quit.@{b}

    RESULT@{ub}
	Returns a pointer to your new @{"IPCData" LINK "dopus/ipc.h/File" 24} handle. The 'data' value that
	was passed to @{"IPC_Launch()" LINK "IPC_Launch"} is stored in the supplied variable.
	If this routine returns NULL, it means an error occurred (either in
	the initialisation of the new process, or in your own initialisation
	code). In this case, you should exit immediately.@{b}

    SEE ALSO@{ub}
	@{"IPC_Launch()" LINK "IPC_Launch"}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "IPC_Reply" "IPC_Reply()"
@{b}

    NAME@{ub}
	IPC_Reply - reply to an IPC message@{b}

    SYNOPSIS@{ub}
	IPC_Reply(msg)
		   A0

	void IPC_Reply(@{"IPCMessage" LINK "dopus/ipc.h/File" 11} *);@{b}

    FUNCTION@{ub}
	Call this routine to reply to IPCMessages you receive at your
	command port (do not call ReplyMsg())@{b}

    INPUTS@{ub}
	msg - message to reply@{b}

    RESULT@{ub}
	The message is replied. It is possible to pass a return code back
	to the sending task (providing the message was sent synchronously).
	To do this, set the 'command' field of the message to the value.
	This will then be the return from the @{"IPC_Command()" LINK "IPC_Command"} function for the
	other process.@{b}

    SEE ALSO@{ub}
	@{"IPC_Launch()" LINK "IPC_Launch"}, @{"IPC_Command()" LINK "IPC_Command"}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Layout_Routines" "Layout_Routines"
@{b}Layout Routines@{ub}

	@{"AddObjectList()        " LINK "AddObjectList"}	@{"AddWindowMenus()          " LINK "AddWindowMenus"}
	@{"BoundsCheckGadget()    " LINK "BoundsCheckGadget"}	@{"BuildMenuStrip()          " LINK "BuildMenuStrip"}
	@{"CheckObjectArea()      " LINK "CheckObjectArea"}	@{"ClearWindowBusy()         " LINK "ClearWindowBusy"}
	@{"CloseConfigWindow()    " LINK "CloseConfigWindow"}	@{"DisableObject()           " LINK "DisableObject"}
	@{"DisplayObject()        " LINK "DisplayObject"}	@{"EndRefreshConfigWindow()  " LINK "EndRefreshConfigWindow"}
	@{"FindMenuItem()         " LINK "FindMenuItem"}	@{"FreeObjectList()          " LINK "FreeObjectList"}
	@{"FreeWindowMenus()      " LINK "FreeWindowMenus"}	@{"GetGadgetValue()          " LINK "GetGadgetValue"}
	@{"GetObject()            " LINK "GetObject"}	@{"GetObjectRect()           " LINK "GetObjectRect"}
	@{"GetWindowAppPort()     " LINK "GetWindowAppPort"}	@{"GetWindowID()             " LINK "GetWindowID"}
	@{"GetWindowMsg()         " LINK "GetWindowMsg"}	@{"LayoutResize()            " LINK "LayoutResize"}
	@{"OpenConfigWindow()     " LINK "OpenConfigWindow"}	@{"ReplyWindowMsg()          " LINK "ReplyWindowMsg"}
	@{"SetConfigWindowLimits()" LINK "SetConfigWindowLimits"}	@{"SetGadgetChoices()        " LINK "SetGadgetChoices"}
	@{"SetGadgetValue()       " LINK "SetGadgetValue"}	@{"SetWindowBusy()           " LINK "SetWindowBusy"}
	@{"SetWindowID()          " LINK "SetWindowID"}	@{"StartRefreshConfigWindow()" LINK "StartRefreshConfigWindow"}

@{b}PURPOSE@{ub}

    1.  The dopus5.library provides font-sensitive layout routines to make it
    easy to create and use a user interface for your application or module. The
    layout code is not as straightforward, or indeed as powerful, as MUI or some
    of the other GUI engines available, and so you might want to consider using
    one of those instead of the DOpus routines.

	The normal procedure in creating an interface is :

	1. Define a list of "objects" (gadgets, text, etc)
	2. Define a window
	3. Call @{"OpenConfigWindow()" LINK "OpenConfigWindow"} to open the window
	4. Call @{"AddObjectList()" LINK "AddObjectList"} to add the objects
	5. Call @{"SetGadgetValue()" LINK "SetGadgetValue"} to initialise gadgets
	6. Message loop with @{"GetWindowMsg()" LINK "GetWindowMsg"}
	7. Call @{"GetGadgetValue()" LINK "GetGadgetValue"} to get gadget final values
	8. Call @{"CloseConfigWindow()" LINK "CloseConfigWindow"} to close the window


    2.  The list of objects is defined as an array of @{"ObjectDef" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 74} structures.
    You call @{"AddObjectList()" LINK "AddObjectList"} to add a list of objects to a window; indeed, you
    can make multiple calls to this function to add multiple lists. Each @{"ObjectDef" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 74}
    structure is defined as follows:

	od_Type

	This field indicates the type of object. Current values are :

	    @{"OD_GADGET" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 116}       - a gadget
	    @{"OD_TEXT" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 117}	 - a text string
	    @{"OD_AREA" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 118}	 - a rectangular area
	    @{"OD_IMAGE" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 119}	- an image

	Two control values are also used:

	    @{"OD_SKIP" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 120}	 - skip this entry
	    @{"OD_END" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 115}	  - ends an @{"ObjectDef" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 74} array


	od_ObjectKind

	If od_Type is set to @{"OD_GADGET" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 116}, this field describes the type of
	gadget. Valid types are:

	    BUTTON_KIND	 - standard push button
	    STRING_KIND	 - a string gadget
	    INTEGER_KIND	- an integer gadget
	    @{"HOTKEY_KIND" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 349}	 - a hotkey field
	    CHECKBOX_KIND       - a checkbox gadget
	    @{"OPUS_LISTVIEW_KIND" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 343}  - an Opus listview gadget
	    PALETTE_KIND	- a palette gadget (pen selection)
	    @{"FILE_BUTTON_KIND" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 344}    - a button that opens a file requester
	    @{"DIR_BUTTON_KIND" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 345}     - a button that opens a directory requester
	    @{"FONT_BUTTON_KIND" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 346}    - a button that opens a font requester
				  (only works under v38 ASL)
	    @{"FRAME_KIND" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 348}	  - a frame (rectangular area)
	    @{"FIELD_KIND" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 347}	  - a readonly string gadget
	    NUMBER_KIND	 - a number display
	    TEXT_KIND	   - a text display

	The above gadgets are all implemented by the dopus5.library. Many are
	similar to their GadTools equivalents. Any GadTools gadget that is not
	replaced by the above types is also available. Currently, these are:

	    LISTVIEW_KIND       - standard GadTools listview
	    MX_KIND	     - radio buttons gadget
	    CYCLE_KIND	  - cycle gadget
	    SCROLLER_KIND       - scroller gadget
	    SLIDER_KIND	 - slider gadget

	If od_Type is @{"OD_AREA" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 118} or @{"OD_TEXT" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 117}, the od_ObjectKind field is used to
	specify the pen used for text rendering. This is not a literal pen
	number but is a DrawInfo pen index (eg TEXTPEN).


	od_CharDims

	This field structure is used to define the character position of the
	object. All objects (and windows, for that matter) have two sets of
	positioning information - character and fine. The character position
	is used to specify the size and position in "font units" - this value
	is scaled for the current font and so allows the display to be
	font-sensitive. A "font unit" is the average width of the font for
	a horizontal coordinate, and the height of the font for a vertical
	coordinate. The "Left" and "Top" fields of the IBox structure control
	the position of the object, and the "Width" and "Height" fields control
	the size.

	There are some magic values for object positioning and sizing. The
	positioning values are:

	    @{"POS_CENTER" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 14}	  - use this in the "Left" or "Top" field to have
				  the object positioned in the center of the
				  window.

	    @{"POS_RIGHT_JUSTIFY" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 15}   - position relative to the right/bottom border

	@{"POS_CENTER" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 14} is an absolute value. @{"POS_RIGHT_JUSTIFY" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 15} is more of a flag,
	used in conjunction with another value. For example, @{"POS_RIGHT_JUSTIFY" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 15}
	by itself would position an object hard up against the right border.
	@{"POS_RIGHT_JUSTIFY" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 15}-2 would position an object at a two 'font unit'
	margin from the border.

	The magic values for sizes are:

	    @{"SIZE_MAXIMUM" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 26}	- the object will be the maximum possible size
				  in this direction

	    @{"SIZE_MAX_LESS" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 27}       - maximum possible size minus an amount

	For example, od_CharDims might be defined as:

	    {@{"POS_CENTER" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 14},@{"POS_RIGHT_JUSTIFY" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 15}-1,@{"SIZE_MAX_LESS" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 27}-4,2}

	This would create an object that was centred in the display, and as
	wide as possible with a two space gap on either side. The object would
	be one space from the bottom border, and be two spaces high.


	od_FineDims

	This field structure is used to define the fine position and size of
	the object. The fine position is given as an absolute pixel value, and
	allows you to make adjustments for GUI components that do not scale
	with the font (eg, borders are always 1 or 2 pixels high, irrespective
	of the font size). You can also make fine adjustments through this
	field when the od_CharDims field uses the POS_ and SIZE_ values.


	od_GadgetText

	This is the locale string ID for the gadget label, or text or area
	string. It must be a valid ID in the locale specified in the
	@{"NewConfigWindow" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 36} structure. If the @{"TEXTFLAG_TEXT_STRING" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 85} flag is set
	for this object, the od_GadgetText field is a pointer to an actual
	text string.


	od_Flags

	The object flags are heavily object dependent. For standard GadTools
	gadgets, the standard GadTools flags apply. Some GadTools flags are
	also applicable to Opus gadgets:

	    PLACETEXT_LEFT
	    PLACETEXT_RIGHT
	    PLACETEXT_ABOVE (only works for some gadgets)
	    PLACETEXT_IN    (only works for some gadgets)

	General purpose Opus flags are:

	    @{"TEXTFLAG_TEXT_STRING" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 85} - this flag is used with all the object
	    types, and indicates that the od_GadgetText field of the @{"ObjectDef" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 74}
	    structure points to a literal text string and not a locale ID.

	    @{"TEXTFLAG_NO_USCORE" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 86} - if you specify this flag, an underscore
	    character in the string will be treated literally. Otherwise,
	    the underscore is used to specify a character to be underscored,
	    indicating a keyboard equivalent.

	Flags for BUTTON_KIND gadgets:

	    @{"BUTTONFLAG_OKAY_BUTTON" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 87} - indicates that this button is an "ok"
	    button. The 'enter' key will automatically be used as a key
	    equivalent for this button. The label for this button is
	    automatically rendered in bold.

	    @{"BUTTONFLAG_CANCEL_BUTTON" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 88} - indicates that this button is a
	    "cancel" button. The 'escape' key will automatically be used as a
	    key equivalent for this button.

	    @{"BUTTONFLAG_TOGGLE_SELECT" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 89} - specifies that you want a toggle-select
	    button (one that can be turned on or off).

	    @{"BUTTONFLAG_THIN_BORDERS" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 91} - specifies that you want 'thin' borders
	    for the button. Thin borders are one pixel wide on all sides,
	    whereas normal borders are two pixels wide on the left and right,
	    and one pixel wide at the top and bottom. This flag can also
	    be used with CHECKBOX_KIND, @{"FRAME_KIND" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 348}, NUMBER_KIND, TEXT_KIND,
	    PALETTE_KIND, @{"FILE_BUTTON_KIND" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 344}, @{"DIR_BUTTON_KIND" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 345} and
	    @{"FONT_BUTTON_KIND" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 346} gadgets.

	Flags for @{"OPUS_LISTVIEW_KIND" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 343} gadgets:

	    @{"LISTVIEWFLAG_CURSOR_KEYS" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 90} - specifies that the cursor keys can
	    be used to scroll up and down in this listview.

	Flags for @{"FILE_BUTTON_KIND" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 344} gadgets:

	    @{"FILEBUTFLAG_SAVE" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 92} - specifies that the file requester is to be
	    opened in save mode.

	Flags for @{"OD_TEXT" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 117} objects:

	    @{"TEXTFLAG_RIGHT_JUSTIFY" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 100} - right justify the text
	    @{"TEXTFLAG_CENTER" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 101}	- center the text

	Flags for @{"OD_AREA" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 118} objects:

	    @{"AREAFLAG_RAISED" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 103} - a raised rectangle
	    @{"AREAFLAG_RECESSED" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 104} - a recessed rectangle
	    @{"AREAFLAG_THIN" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 105} - draw rectangle with thin borders
	    @{"AREAFLAG_ICON" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 106} - draw an icon drop box
	    @{"AREAFLAG_ERASE" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 107} - erase the interior of the rectangle
	    @{"AREAFLAG_LINE" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 108} - draw a separator line
	    @{"AREAFLAG_OPTIM" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 109} - optimised refreshing when updating
	    @{"AREAFLAG_TITLE" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 110} - draw a group box with a title
	    @{"AREAFLAG_NOFILL" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 111} - don't fill interior


	od_ID

	This is the ID of the object. If the object is a gadget, it will
	also set the gadget ID.


	od_TagList

	Object-specific taglist. For GadTools gadgets, all the standard
	GadTools flags apply.

	    @{"GTCustom_LocaleLabels" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 290} - (USHORT *)

	    Used with : MX_KIND, CYCLE_KIND

	    This tag points to an array of locale IDs. It allows you to
	    specify the text contents of the gadgets using locale. The array
	    must be terminated with a 0 value. You can use this instead of
	    the GTCY_Labels or GTMX_Labels tags.


	    @{"GTCustom_Image" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 291} - (struct Image *)

	    Used with : BUTTON_KIND

	    Points to an Image structure that defines an image to be displayed
	    within the button.


	    @{"GTCustom_CallBack" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 292} - (void __asm (*)(register __a1 struct TagItem *,
						register __a2 struct Window *))

	    Used with : All types

	    This tag allows you to specify the address of a callback function
	    that is called when the object is added to the window via
	    @{"AddObjectList()" LINK "AddObjectList"}. The callback function is passed both the window
	    pointer and a pointer to the tag. The function can modify both the
	    ti_Tag and ti_Data values of the tag, and when it returns the
	    Tag will be re-evaluated with the new contents.


	    @{"GTCustom_LayoutRel" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 293} - USHORT

	    Used with : All types

	    Lets you position objects relative to another. The ti_Data field
	    contains the ID of an object that *has previously been added*
	    (eg is before this one in the @{"ObjectDef" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 74} array). The new object
	    will be positioned relative to the specified object; from the
	    new object's point of view, coordinate 0,0 is the top-left
	    corner of the relative object. You can use @{"POS_CENTER" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 14} and the
	    other magic position values with this tag. For example, to
	    position an object in the center of another one, you would
	    use the @{"GTCustom_LayoutRel" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 293} tag, and set char_dims.Left and
	    char_dims.Top for the new object to @{"POS_CENTER" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 14}.

	    If the window is resizeable, you must supply the @{"GTCustom_CopyTags" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 302}
	    tag as well.


	    @{"GTCustom_LayoutPos" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 315} - USHORT

	    Used with : All types

	    Lets you position objects based on the position of another object.
	    The ti_Data field contains the ID of an object that must have been
	    previously added. This tag is used in conjunction with the
	    following object flags:

