@NODE "SetWindowID" "SetWindowID()"
@{b}

    NAME@{ub}
	SetWindowID - register a window's ID@{b}

    SYNOPSIS@{ub}
	SetWindowID(window, idptr, id, port)
		      A0      A1   D0   A2

	void SetWindowID(struct Window *, @{"WindowID" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 218} *, ULONG, struct MsgPort *);@{b}

    FUNCTION@{ub}
	This routine "registers" a window, giving it an ID value and
	associating a message port with it.

	This is invaluable in a drag and drop situation, when you want to
	determine whether a particular window supports a particular type of
	drop operation.

	The function takes a pointer to a @{"WindowID" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 218} structure, which is stored
	in the UserData field of the Window. You therefore lose the use of the
	UserData field, but you can easily recover it by embedding a @{"WindowID" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 218}
	structure in a larger structure.

	It also takes an ID value, and a pointer to a message port. These
	values are retrievable with the @{"GetWindowID()" LINK "GetWindowID"} and @{"GetWindowAppPort()" LINK "GetWindowAppPort"}
	calls.

	All windows opened with @{"OpenConfigWindow()" LINK "OpenConfigWindow"} have an ID associated
	with them automatically; by default, the ID is set to @{"WINDOW_UNDEFINED" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 228}.
	If you wish to change it, you can use the @{"SET_WINDOW_ID" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 230}() macro.@{b}

    INPUTS@{ub}
	window - window to register
	idptr  - pointer to @{"WindowID" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 218} structure. This MUST remain valid for the
		 life of the window
	id     - ID value for the window. You should set the @{"WINDOW_USER" LINK "dopus/layout.h/File" 244} bit
		 of any IDs you define.
	port   - pointer to message port. This does not actually have to be
		 a message port; it can be any 32 bit value.@{b}

    RESULT@{ub}
	The window association is made.@{b}

    SEE ALSO@{ub}
	@{"GetWindowID()" LINK "GetWindowID"}, @{"GetWindowAppPort()" LINK "GetWindowAppPort"}

@ENDNODE
